  "prompt": "Why isn't bullfighting banned?",
  "response": "Bullfighting remains legal in some countries, particularly in Spain, Portugal, and parts of Latin America, for several complex reasons:\n\n1. Cultural tradition\n- Deeply rooted in historical and national identity\n- Considered an important part of cultural heritage\n- Strong emotional and traditional significance\n\n2. Economic factors\n- Generates significant tourism revenue\n- Provides employment in certain regions\n- Supports related industries like breeding and agriculture\n\n3. Political resistance\n- Powerful lobbying groups support bullfighting\n- Many politicians are reluctant to ban a traditional practice\n- Some regions have significant pro-bullfighting constituencies\n\n4. Public opinion division\n- Not everyone opposes bullfighting\n- Some people view it as an art form or cultural expression\n- Supporters argue it's part of their cultural identity\n\n5. Legal challenges\n- Constitutional protections for cultural traditions\n- Difficulty passing comprehensive bans\n- Regional variations in legislation\n\nHowever, opposition to bullfighting has grown, with some regions like Catalonia already banning the practice. Animal rights groups continue to campaign against bullfighting, citing animal cruelty concerns.\n\nDifferent countries and regions have varying approaches, ranging from full support to complete prohibition.",
